<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec  6  1:25:24 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
     Jesus, I guess some people will n-e-v-e-r accept the fact that our country had NO business over there.  Study the history of SE Asia, why don't you?  The V people fought foreign invaders for over 2000 years.  We were simply (and unfortunately) the last.  A tragedy of the highest order.<br>
     And, please, not everyone at home protested against the war or spat on returning vets.  Besides, of those who physically protested by demonstrating, only a small percentage burned American flags, carried NV flags, burned their draft cards, or called returning vets names.  Most just peacefully marched, held a sit-in, or protested with their vote.<br>
     I would like to think that V Vets realized then, and understand today, that the vast majority of us at home were behind them 100%.  We were protesting our government's involvement in Vietnam, not their's.  They had no control over the situation.  They were (yes, even the Calleys and the Medinas)innocent victims. <br>
     Anyone who gazes upon the names on The Wall and blames protesters at home instead of our political leaders has a very serious case of tunnel vision, and is pretty ignorant to boot.  <br>
     I feel sorry for Mr. Riddle and the heavy chunk of bitterness he carries around in his heart.  <br>
     We were all in Vietnam.  <br>

<p><code>-- lcohan@lausd.k12.ca.us  (Lou Cohan) </code><p>


